CLINICAL HISTORY:  Epilepsy, currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:   Lamictal, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 38-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy, current seizure­
free.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Digital video EEG is performed using standard
10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation. This is an awake through stage II sleep record in an individual who is very drowsy.
In maximum wakefulness there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves are noted in sleep, as are post.
Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background slowing. The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits but excessively drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted. The excessive drowsiness can be due to sleep deprivations, medications or a warm environment.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with episodes of bilateral hand shaking and
loss of awareness. These episodes stopped after the patient began Depakote therapy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were preformed. This was a 1 hour sleep-deprived study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing and anterior
spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background
slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this
EEG nor in the previous EEG. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old left handed male with migraine headaches and visual scintillations.  Head trauma.

MEDICATIONS:  Enalapril, Zocor, Glucosamine, ASA, Insulin

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, background EEG includes a well organized 10 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness produces an increase in background theta. POSTS are observed in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. The patient drifts back into stage I sleep.

HR: 	60 bpm

IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:    38 year old right handed woman with migraine headaches, depression and a sharp pain in her head.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Seroquel, Zolpidem, Nabumetone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG is well-organized. There is a relatively fast alpha rhythm of 12 Hz with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces an increased in amplitude of the background. This is followed by a drowsy and then stage I sleep with vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed concurrently and do not active the record. In fact, the patient seems to drift into stage II sleep at the close of this study.
HR: 	66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	69 year old  right handed male, with recurrent episodes of lightheadedness lasting 4 hours, multiple medical problems.

MEDICATIONS: Zocor, Quinine, Cardura

CLINICAL HISTORY:	22 year old right handed woman with severe asthma and episodes of right sided shaking, trembling, loss of consciousness, and incontinence. These have occurred in clusters for the past 2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol, Prednisone,  Primacort.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Drowsiness increases the synchronicity of the record.
HR: 	60-70 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed.  Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed male with head trauma in 1982, now losing track of time, depression,  anxiety, forgetfulness. Episodes of forgetfulness increasing in stress but none for the last month.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Glyburide, Actoplus, Aceon
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Occasional temporal wicket is observed. The patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background followed by drowsiness.  More extensive stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are observed later on in the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The wicket activity described above is a normal variant.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39 year old right handed male with daily headaches, evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine,  Zolpidem, Elavil, Cymbalta, Norvasc, Gabapentin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and primarily asleep EEG with photic stimulation but without hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage I and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and posts.   The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and has limited wakefulness.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  The primarily sleep EEG could be due to sleep deprivation or other disturbances like hypersomnolence, or even a sleep-deprived EEG. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   48 year old male with a history of tremor during sleep which began in July 2009.  The patient has a history of an MVA in June 2009 and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Valtrex, Nexium, Singulair, Metoprolol, Verapamil, Furosemide, Doxazosin, Flax seed oil, Omega fish oil.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low-voltage but well­ defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Features of drowsiness include an increase of beta.  Hyperventilation produces background slowing.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, and a low-voltage pattern is a normal finding.

IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. Normal

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with a feeling of disequilibrium
and presyncope, admitted in July 2009.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10
Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an
increase in background slowing. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes,
spindles and POSTS. The patient is quite sleepy and transitions in and out of stage II
sleep. The POSTS are of slightly higher amplitude on the left. Hyperventilation
produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The
amplitude asymmetry of the POSTS is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old female presented with syncope and toe ulceration.
MEDICATIONS: Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the
record. There is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified. Features of drowsiness
including increase in beta followed by vertexes, K complexes, and spindles. With
arousal, the patient does achieve an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed in the
record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	28 year old woman with multiple events in the clinic today admitted with episode of unresponsiveness  and mutism.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.  The patient is awake and cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a well defined 9.3 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage fronto-central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by the appearance of rhythmic theta.
HR: 	90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Of note, this record was
recorded immediately after this patient's multiple and prolonged events. Hence, not only were the behaviors unusual for seizures, but there was no postictal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   59 year old right handed female with headaches and sharp occipital pain.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is awake for most of the study, however, is in and out of drowsiness.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG shows a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with 25 mV.  In addition, when drowsy the patient has 5 Hz temporal waves and some vertex waves.  Also noted is a rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness (RMTD) which is a normal variant, entered during photic stimulation.  The patient is seen to have driving at 7 Hz.



HR  :


84 bpm with occasional PVCs when drowsy.



IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy  Clinical evaluation of PVCs in sleep may be valuable.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic simulation was completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. Lambda waves are observed in the background. IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Lambda waves are a normal phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a loss of consciousness this past Monday, hypersomnolence today prior to thyroidectomy. Ongoing confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Ventolin, Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage II  sleep with vertex, K complexes and spindles.  Little testing is performed to assess for cognitive testing.  The patient is stimulated and when she is awake, the background includes a well-defined, 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates an excessively sleepy individual but normal awake through stage II sleep.  Morphology or wave forms are noted. Additional evaluation for the cause for her excessive drowsiness might be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	41   year old right handed male with recurrent panic attacks and syncopal episodes.
MEDICATIONS:  Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.   This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness including increasing beta.  Brief stage II sleep is observed followed by spontaneous arousals.  Hyperventilation produces an increasing amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep and does elicit scant driving.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed. The sleepiness and the generalized beta may be due to the patient's medications.

voltage. There is a defined 8 to 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Features of
drowsiness including increase in background slowing. Because of the trauma, there is
some electrode artifact. Features of drowsiness including increase in background beta.
HR: 72 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Despite the
history of recurrent subdural hematomas, there are no epileptiform features noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	31 year old man with history of generalized tonic clonic activity during sleep with post ictal unresponsiveness x 3-5 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a very drowsy study. The patient drifts in and out of sleep during the entirety of the study. He does have a background alpha rhythm of 11 Hz. There is also the presence of POSTS, and slow rolling eye movements. During photic stimulation, there is a mild driving response until the patient falls asleep.  Hyperventilation creates an increased amplitude.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There is no epileptiform activity. This was an otherwise normal EEG. Drowsiness may be related to sleep-deprived EEG, however the sleep is not sustained. This may be related to a sleep disorder. Normal EEG's do not exclude epilepsy. Based on clinical correlation, a repeat EEG may be warranted to find focal
features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	80 year old woman with recent trauma status post fall due to unsteady gait. Had episode of eye twitching and myoclonic jerking of the arms and episodically of the legs. Indications to rule out seizure activity. Past medical history of A. fib, TIA, pacemaker.

MEDICATIONS:  Cymbalta, Percocet,  ASA,Cymbalta, Clonazepam, Vicodin, Lovenox, Lotensin, Norvasc, Loratadine

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  of EKG. Photic simulation was performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is a well-organized symmetric EEG. There is alpha of 8-9 Hz throughout the record. The amplitude is mildly high for patient's age but this is nonspecific. There is some muscle artifact due to shaking episodes, however there are no EEG correlates to the shaking activity. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

HR: 	72 bpm and  regular.


IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:   There is no epileptiform activity. There are no focal features. This study is improved compared to prior EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with learning disability, seizure free since
2007. Previous history of vertex sharp wave.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awaken and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively
low voltage. There is excess theta in the background and a hint of 9 Hz alpha rhythm.
Later portions of the record demonstrate a more vigorous 10 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the patient is drifting into stage
2 sleep.
HR: 56 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed in this record
today. There were only on 1 occasion some focal theta in the right central temporal
region. The only other abnormality is really an excess of theta or a variable degree of
background slowing or disorganization. On the whole, these findings are less prominent
than in previous studies. Many years ago there was a vertex spike while awake, but that
was not seen today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old male with recurrent episodes of syncope for the past 2 years. This occurs twice a week where he feels lightheaded, dizzy and hot and awakens on the floor having hit his head.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

In this individual with a history of epilepsy, additional EEG recordings may be valuable to delineate underlying epileptiform activity as well as to determine if there is an epileptiform discharge hidden in the hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Hypnagogic hypersynchrony, however, is a normal finding.

HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The initial sections of the record demonstrate a sedated pattern compatible with acute postoperative state, but by the end the patient is awake and there are no pathologic findings. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study in the lab maybe of use.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake through stage
II sleep. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.8 Hz alpha rhythm with
a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. The patient transitions rapidly
between wakefulness and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and
POSTS. On one occasion as she is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep, during
photic stimulation, it appears that there is new or alpha activity on the right, almost as
there are vertex waves and POSTS. Photic stimulation produces supraharmonic driving
responses which can be differentiated from the patient drifting in and out of sleep, and,
in fact, she has a harmonic that is unusual in that it sometimes to be 3 or 5 times the
frequency of flash stimuli.
HR: 60 bpm with occasional PVC's.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above are interesting and unusual
but not necessarily pathological in nature. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis
of epilepsy. A review of this patient's history may be helpful because significant sleep
deprivation might account for some of the features described above.

Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep and does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The findings described above with rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness are considered a normal variant. However, they can also be seen in individuals with epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration a follow up study is suggested.

Abundant stage II sleep includes vertex, K complexes, spindles and POSTS. On one occasion in hyperventilation, there is a single burst of shifting slowing. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing scant slowing and an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not clearly activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. This EEG may be compared to 2004 EEG as well as other prior studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 70 year old right handed gentleman with intermittent paroxysmal
vertigo.
MEDICATIONS: Combigan, Glipizide, Simvastatin, Metformin, Meclizine, quinapril,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed.in lab using standard 20-20
system of electrode with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 30 Hz 30 microvolt alpha
rhythm with a slow amount of low voltage frontal central beta. Hyperventilation is
performed early on in the record producing a small amount of theta. Drowsiness is
characterized by an increase in background beta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral
driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If this patient's paroxysmal vertigo is
thought to be a seizure, consideration for outpatient EEG monitoring is appropriate to
more completely capture his spells.

HISTORY: 63 year old right handed male left carotid stenosis.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20

OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the EEG

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old woman with a seizure in October, previously seizure free for many years.
MEDICATIONS: Dyazide, Clonidine, Risperdal.
INTRODUCTION; Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is almost an exclusive sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Most of the record includes stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles and POSTS. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep. Hyperventilation is also performed while the patient is relatively drowsy with a beta frequency pattern and scant 10 hertz alpha. There are some minor electrode artifacts noted in the background.
HR: N/A
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to a previous study which identifies slightly asymmetric POSTS, this study is symmetric although there is some electrode artifacts. There were no epileptiform features. In addition, there were no normal variants which resemble epileptiform features although there was scant amount of artifact and 1 or 2 rare bursts of shifting symmetry irrespective of the artifacts. There are no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old right handed male with syncope, numbness,
paresthesias, recurrent loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
Hyperventilation was omitted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is asleep during much of the EEG. with
abundant stage II sleep, vertex, POSTS, K-complexes and spindles. There is excess
artifact but there also appears to be attenuation on the right. Multiple artifacts are noted
from the left occipital region which are not corrected during the EEG. Photic stimulation
is performed while the patient is asleep. Very little stimulation of the patient is performed
and this stimulation Is performed within the last few minutes of the test and does not
serve to alert the patient.
HR: 60bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL This EEG include electrode artifact on the right as well as
an inability to adequately stimulate the patient. Consequently focal features may be
under recognized. In addition, additional testing to make sure that it is possible to record
an awake individual is necessary.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old left handed male with headaches associated with

CLINICAL HISTORY: 24 year old man with new-onset seizures. History of head

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old right-handed woman with seizures for the last 5
years. The patient reports an aura of feeling hot then tonic/clonic seizures with loss of
consciousness, last seizure 2 weeks ago. Patient says she buys Xanax off the streets.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax.
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz, 40 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm in a background rich in beta frequency activity. Drowsiness
is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in beta. Deeper
stages of sleep are not achieved. Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the
record. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response with harmonic and super
harmonic driving. In addition, the patient starts to be just a bit sleepier with some
rhythmic theta at the beginning of photic stimulation.
HR: 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL There are no epileptiform features. The generous beta
may be due to this patient's medications. The vigorous driving response is a normal
phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old right handed female with complex partial epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with epilepsy, hepatitis C and liver
disease admitted after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were
performed. The patient had one of his spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm with
occasional background theta particularly in the temporal regions. Hyperventilation is performed
early-on in the record producing an increase in generalized slowing. This is follow by
drowsiness with increased rhythmic slowing followed by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles
and then arousals.
At 11:59, the patient is awake. He shifts about. He is awake during photic stimulation which
elicits a brief driving response.
The patient has a spell during the EEG. This is at 12:10. at 12:10:56, he is moving about. He is
unresponsive with a technician. During the section at 12:10:52, the patient has right facial
twitching and he has some movements of his left arm. He does not answer questions to the
technologist. The patient is not entirely on camera. The EEG demonstrates an awake pattern
with an artifact at C3T3. He is amnestic for the event. Unfortunately during this spell the
technician is trying to repair the C3 electrode. He is described as having alternating right facial
or left hand movements. There is no definitive EEG signature for these behaviors.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits but with unusual behavior.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the electrode problems, there was no EEG scalp
signature for this patient's behavior.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old male with recurrent blackout spells and a history of an aneurysm and a heart attack.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old right handed male with new onset seizure activity. Evaluate for alcohol-withdrawal seizures 4/3/2011.
MEDICATIONS: Serax, Keppra, Ativan
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake through stage 2 sleep in a very drowsy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The overall alpha rhythm is relatively low voltage, 12 Hz. Rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness characteristic 5-6 Hz is identified in the transition to sleep. Vertex waves and spindles are noted. The patient continues to have eye movement into stage 2 sleep. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is falling back into stage 2 sleep, but does elicit scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are a number of normal variants in the EEG, including rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness. The overall background is very low voltage and there is generous beta. The generous beta may be due to the use of benzodiazepines. The low voltage background is not pathological in and of itself.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed woman with new-onset seizures as of February 15, 2011.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with episodes which are described as spasms. They include eye fluttering, head rocking and crying. Her brother and her child both have epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient had one of her behavioral events during the EEG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a symmetric, 11 Hz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a great deal of blinking. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of theta and some bursts of rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Photic stimulation elicits abundant, symmetric driving. The patient has an event during photic stimulation characterized by frequent eye blink. The eye blink frequency increases after the photic stimulation stops. She has shaking of her legs and impaired responsiveness. This is followed by moaning. No epileptiform features are associated with these behaviors. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout these behaviors which began at 11:44. unfortunately, the camera is primarily on her face and upper body and this is the lower extremity activity. Afterward, the patient has intermittent arm shaking noted at 11:47, again difficult to see on the camera. Afterward she feels drained and tired but the EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second EEG for this individual. During both EEGs, the patient had behaviors characteristic of nonepileptic seizures with characteristic behavior, crying in the absence of epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed gentleman with a long history of depression, epilepsy, cerebral palsy, subsequent aneurysm repair. Last seizure 05/11/2011 with loss of consciousness and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Dilantin, Norvasc, Simvastatin, Sertraline, Amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and scant alpha rhythms. A breech rhythm is noted in the right hemisphere. There is also some electrode artifact, compatible with a deformity of the skull shape.
Hyperventilation is performed early in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude, augmenting the double phase reversing artifacts on the right and increasing some theta a bit more so on the right compared to the left. Features of drowsiness included increase in beta. In drowsiness, the focal slowing is a bit more apparent on the right with a mixture of rhythmic 3-5 Hz activity. Vertex waves are noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep. There is  disruption of faster frequency activity on the right in the transition to sleep in the centrotemporal regions with a bit more prominent spindles in the central regions, in the region of the previous
craniotomy. Overall, most of the focal slowing in this record is centrotemporal. In the context of a breech rhythm, there are a handful of right central or frontal sharp waves. Photic stimulation is  performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep. No significant driving response was noted.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: A normal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic theta and delta activity in the right temporal region.
2. Rare G4 and F4 sharp waves identified in the context of a breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, the EEG today has primarily centrotemporal slowing. The sharp waves are ipsilateral to the previous craniotomy and similar to the previous records. There is some variability in terms of localization of epileptiform activity
in the right for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female with seizures since age 14, presents with refractory episodes, here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta activity seen diffusely throughout the EEG.  During the recording, the patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  The only activating procedure that is performed is hyperventilation, during which she has an episode which I will describe below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Events:  During this recording, while the patient was doing hyperventilation she suddenly stopped responding, started moving her throat and jerking her back and forth repeatedly.  At times she would move to the left and then to the right.  During this episode, the tech stimulated her feet and she would respond and at times appeared to follow commands, but would not verbalize.  The whole episode of unresponsiveness lasted some minutes, but with the clinical presentation lasted about 12 minutes.  During this recording, the EEG revealed prominent muscle artifact but a nice posterior dominant rhythm could be seen at times and normal EEG could be seen at times throughout the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG with an episode of unresponsiveness as described above with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a nonepileptic event, likely psychogenic in nature.  Otherwise this is a normal awake EEG and no seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with new onset of seizures who was unconsciousness, unable to speak, and left face twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, patient events, and alarms, as well as nurses events were noted to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and normal stages I to III with sleep are recorded.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Episodes:  The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording.  The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching.  This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again.
The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m.  The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive.  This was followed by staring and mouth movements.  The episode lasted for over 4 minutes.
At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching.  This was much more severe than the other ones.  She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive.  Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion.  The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes.
The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG and 3 non-epileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  Note:  The 3 events described above did not have an EEG correlate which is consistent with a diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  39 year old right handed male with history of right ankle pain and narcotic abuse, now with episodes of loss of consciousness with diffuse body shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside for 4.5 hours using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, as well as patient alarm events, and nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm with normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Events:  The patient had about 9 events which consisted of him pressing the alarm, suddenly his arms would become flexed, and he would become stiff and grimacing his face, lasting for about 20-30 seconds, during the episode and after which he would be unresponsive for another 2-3 minutes.  The behavior was very similar to the ones that he described before and every episode remained the same.  During these episodes the EEG would have a diffuse muscle artifact, but underlying it there would be a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform discharges prior to the flexing, posturing, or after when he would remain unresponsive.  It looked like a normal EEG.  Sometimes with the flexor posturing he would hip thrust during the event.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG with events with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The events that were captured and described as above had no EEG correlate and are consistent with psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.  No epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  19 year old left handed male admitted on April 22, 2012 with new onset seizure characterized by loss of consciousness, face falling forward from a standing position, with 2 minute tonic clonic seizure, followed by 5-10 minutes of confusion.  Past history of seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Percocet,
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm of 40 mV.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in theta, following this the patient becomes drowsy with attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in both beta and theta.  Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep.  Vertex waves are slightly asymmetric.
In stage I and stage II sleep frontal beta is quite prominent. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.  The patient is drifting into and out of stage II sleep during photic stimulation, which does not otherwise activate the record.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Asymmetry in the vertex waves could be related to a head measuring error, therefore, this should not be considered pathological.

Rhythmic temporal theta drowsiness appears as the patient transitions into drowsiness and then very brief stage I sleep. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep.  There is scant driving, but again the temporal theta.

LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/19/2012 to 06/20/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes.  The first is on the 19th at noon where she felt a little startled.  The second was at 10 p.m. where she felt a mini aura characterized by tingling sensation on her face.  She did not recall an episode at 5:25, although she did push the button for a tingling sensation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep includes a well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity.
Event time 11:22:  There is a burst of rhythmic left temporal theta delta with frequency evolution.  This is 5 seconds in duration.  There is no push button at that time.
Event time 5:25:20 p.m.:   A burst of rhythmic theta, frequency was subtle, frequency evolution lasting only 3 seconds.  Thirty seconds later the patient reports the mini-aura which she no longer recalled.
Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12- 72 – 06/20/2012 TO 06/21/2012
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a well defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is a sleep deprived record.  Around 10:00 p.m. the patient seems to be trying to stay up.  The EEG demonstrates small EPOCHS where the patient seems to be drowsy.   Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K-complexes, and spindles. The data is reviewed for the clinical symptoms that the patient experienced, but no epileptiform features are identified.
HR:    66 bpm
LONG TERM MONITORING - # 12-72 – 06/21/2012 TO 06/22/2012
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  The patient reported an aura at 8 p.m. on the 21st.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Around 8 p.m., the patient is noted to transition in and out of stage 2 sleep, waking up and falling back asleep.  Fragments of deeper stages of sleep are noted overnight.
No electrographic seizures were identified.  The seizure and spike detector did not identify any other epileptiform abnormalities.
Event time 11:55:  The patient pushes the button at 11:56:12 stating that she feels as if she is about to have an aura.  She puts her hand to her chest and later appears to be tearful.  The EEG is awake at this time.  No epileptiform features were noted.   For her 8:00 p.m. the patient reported symptoms that her throat was closing with the seizure.

HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
3 bursts of rhythmic, paroxysmal theta, all less than 4 seconds in duration, but with frequency evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's clinical symptoms did not appear to be associated with well-defined epileptiform abnormalities.  On one day, however, there were discharges which appear epileptiform in nature.  While this patient did not have any of her larger spells with head turning, a feeling as if her throat was closing or impairment of awareness, this record does not exclude a diagnosis and clinically, diagnosis may be considered.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient's EEG was reviewed using continuous spike and seizure detection software, in addition to the patient's learned event as well as nurses' notes.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a mild excessive amount of beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and stage III sleep, as well as stage IV.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   None
SEIZURE/EVENT:  During the recording, the patient presses the alarm around 7:39 p.m. and describes that she feels like she is going to have an event.  There are no EEG changes at that time.  At 09:24:51, the patient presses the alarm and starts shaking her body, arching her back, and stretching her legs.  She lifts up the sheets at times and cannot be seen in the video.  She continues to do this for about 7 to 8 minutes until nurses come in and she is unresponsive to questions.  She remains having irregular jerking movements.  During this entire time, the EEG remains normal with no epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The episode captured during this EEG had no EEG correlate, which is consistent with a nonepileptic psychogenic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  31 year old right handed gentleman with 1-year history of epilepsy.  The patient was a steel worker who fell 20-30 feet 2 years ago.  Suffered a loss of consciousness.  Patient's seizures occur every 1-2 months and are preceded by 24 hours of nausea, vomiting, then loss of consciousness, tonic-clonic activity and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  The drowsy pattern is relatively symmetric and on rare occasions, the slow activity seems to be slightly slower on the right compared to the left.  This is more apparent with the use of frequency analysis.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral theta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous, bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.  There is vigorous harmonic driving and supraharmonic driving identified from both hemispheres.  The driving response is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right, but the overall frequency differences are relatively symmetric.  On some occasions, the supraharmonic driving seems to be bit a more prominent on the right.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:   EEG is at the limit of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Simple visual analysis of the EEG would not otherwise identify the subtle asymmetries described above.  In this individual with head trauma, the subtle features on the right may be evaluated by imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed woman with life long migraine headaches, now with an early morning headache with lightheadedness and dry mouth, but without visual phenomenon. INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Mu activity, as well as lambda was identified. The patient appears to be very sleepy, transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Spindle activity is noted.  There seem to be fragments of sleep spindles just as she is dropping almost in and out wakefulness.  As the sleep record continues, more abundant stage II sleep is identified, but in the transition in and out of stage II sleep, there are fragments of early drowsiness, almost emerging into a stage II sleep pattern. The patient is awakened at the end of the test and answers complex questions. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

IMPRESSION:  Somewhat unusual, but normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features, but there are multiple normal variants, including mu and rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness. Given the transitions noted early in the record between wakefulness and stage II sleep, an underlying sleep deficit may account for this.  If there is any other question, a follow up study when the patient has had adequate sleep may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old man with a history of TBI in 1998, admitted after having an episode of tonic-clonic seizure, brought to the emergency department where he had another seizure and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Pantoprazole, Depakote
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient's impedances were inappropriate, specifically in the occipital electrodes which caused some multi-electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that appears to reach 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient had some normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures did not produce any abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I/stage II.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
One single sharp transient maximal at F3 seen in the recording while drowsy.
Occasional small amplitude sharp spikes seen at T3, only in stage I sleep, although not seen over T2.  The morphology is most consistent with benign epileptiform transients of sleep (BETS).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal limited EEG with one suspicious left frontal sharp transient and BETS.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The significance of the left frontal sharp transient is unclear.  A repeated recording should be performed.  Particularly in this patient where the impedances and the quality of the recording was poor, it should be repeated free of charge.  The BETS are benign and do not indicate a high correlation with an epileptogenic focus in that region.

Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage 1, stage 2 and deeper stages of sleep.

EVENTS:  The patient had 2 events in this recording similar to the ones in the previous day.  The first one occurred at 8:10:43 p.m. and the second one occurred at 11:47 p.m.  Both of them, the body had irregular shaking for minutes with no response to verbal or motor commands.  The patient had no EEG correlate during this time despite being unconscious.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The 2 episodes described above had no EEG correlate, as such it is consistent with nonepileptic seizures.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

The background consists of very low amplitude diffuse fast activity without clear posterior dominant rhythm.  During hyperventilation bursts of diffuse delta are observed.  Photic stimulation does not result in change in the background.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Sinus bradycardia with heart rate of less than 60 beats per minute is captured in a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Sinus bradycardia.
Excess beta.
No sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake-only EEG.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, but stage II sleep is not recorded.  If clinical diagnosis for seizures persists, a
repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  Sinus bradycardia with heart rate of less than 60 is captured in a single EKG lead.

There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During sleep, vertex waves and bursts of theta are captured; however, stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation produces mild diffuse background slowing.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  Sinus bradycardia with heart rate less than 60 beats a minute is captured on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Sinus bradycardia.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep is not recorded.  If clinical suspicion for seizures persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  Sinus bradycardia with heart rate less than 60 is captured in a single EKG lead.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a diffusely slow pattern.  Sections of the record include stage II sleep with spindles and posts.  Stimulation of the patient produces a brief arousal with a 9-Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  This is followed by a somewhat slower pattern.
Heart rate 114 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.  When the patient is first stimulated, there is a normal awake pattern and then some background slowing, compatible with a drowsy patient.  Clinical correlation regarding the patient's hypersomnolence may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old woman admitted for a syncopal episode lasting 10-15 minutes followed by lethargy and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake through stage 2 sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Mu activity was identified, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  The patient transitions readily into stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles and POSTs.
Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.  This seems to be a very drowsy patient.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 69-year-old woman with extensive coronary artery disease who now presents with 7 to 10 days of episodes of passing out.  Of note, while she was in the doctor's office she was observed to have right arm shaking, followed by eyes rolling back and then loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Plavix, aspirin, Singulair, Keppra, Ativan, isosorbide, metoprolol, Lipitor, and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated low to moderate amplitude 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Lambda waves are occasionally captured.  During sleep, vertex waves, sleep spindles, K complexes, and POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep) are captured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.  A regular rate is noted on the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 22 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes and 55 seconds.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient history:  The patient is a 47-year-old man with past medical history of seizures since childhood.  Last seizure occurred in August of 2012.  Seizures are characterized as generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  MRI of the brain shows encephalomalacia/gliosis in the right parietal lobe consistent with chronic infarct.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications:  Coumadin, Keppra, Lamictal, Tylenol, Motrin, Prilosec.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9 to 10 Hz alpha that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  During drowsiness, the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and rare vertex waves are captured. Hyperventilation produces mild, diffuse background slowing.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
No focal slowing.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy nearly 24 minutes EEG.   No epileptiform discharges are captured; however, stage II sleep is not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizure still persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.

MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Crestor and a sleeping pill.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10 Hz activity that attenuates with eyes opening. There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Excess beta is captured.  During sleep, sleep spindles and POSTS (posterior occipital sharp transients of sleep) are captured.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Photic stimulation produce no change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 40 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 26-year-old woman with a longstanding history of seizures, now with increased seizure frequency for the last approximately month and a half.  Seizures are described as general tonic-clonic convulsions associated with occasional tongue biting, lethargy and self-injury.
MEDICATIONS:  Include Keppra, Tegretol and Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of moderate amplitude 8.5 Hz alpha that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is no anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  Excess beta is present throughout the recording.  During brief drowsiness, increase in diffuse beta activity is captured.  Hyperventilation does not produce significant change in the background.  Photic stimulation at multiple flash frequencies results in bilateral symmetrical driving at the medium-to-high range flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 22-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  However, stage 2 sleep is not recorded.  If clinical suspicion for epilepsy persists, a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  Excess beta could be seen as a result of medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.

Heart rate 66.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Refractory epilepsy.

Continuous spike detection software as well as seizure detection software in addition to patient events and nurses' notes were used to review the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Events or seizures:  None reported.  No push-buttons were noted in this 4 day study
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep LTM EEG.  No events were captured.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 44-year-old man with a past medical history of a motor vehicle accident with a result in head trauma on 09/19/2012.  The patient now reports a single episode of staring that lasts for a few seconds.  The patient also complains of seeing (black floaters) intermittently across his visual fields.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.    Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of  well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  This alpha activity is higher in amplitude over the right.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with higher frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During very brief drowsiness at the end of the recording bursts of diffuse polymorphic theta and delta is captured.  Hyperventilation does not result in significant change in the background.  Stepped stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy 24 minute EEG.  The asymmetry of posterior dominant rhythm observed is within normal limits.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, Stage II sleep is not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizure persists a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 26-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures, now is admitted with increase in seizure frequency.  Continuous audio/video EEG recording is performed for differential diagnosis of her events.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra 250 in the morning and then stopped and Tegretol 400 mg twice a day.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode placement and a single EKG lead.  There was also audio and visual recording performed simultaneously. Spike detection and seizure detection were activated.  Medical house officer's notes and nursing staff notes as well as pushbutton events were reviewed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Lambda waves are captured.  Sleep architecture consists of POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), vertex waves, sleep spindles, K complexes, slow wave sleep and multiple epochs of REM sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There were no events captured.
FINDINGS:  No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal 24-hour awake and asleep audio/video EEG.  There were no events captured in the 24-hour period.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 18-year-old with epilepsy since age 2, now with seizures every 3 weeks, prior to menstruation.  The patient feels hot, has a headache, screams, stares, makes a noise in her throat, and then is confused for 1 to 2 minutes.  History of ADHD.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, clonidine, Zyrtec, and Concerta.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Unfortunately, this patient was not able to get to sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm.  Posterior slow waves of youth were identified.  Hyperventilation produced some muscle artifact and the patient was noted to be giggling during hyperventilation.  Photic stimulation did not elicit a driving response.  Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in the record.  In this young adult with relatively frequent seizures, a repeat recording closer to the time of her catamenial epilepsy might be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old with headaches and bilateral eye twitching lasting 1 minute.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-developed, 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  The patient transitions in and out stage II sleep.  Vertex waves and spindles were seen in stage II sleep. In relaxed wakefulness, occasional eye flutter was observed.
Photic stimulation was not possible.  The patient was observed to have some eye blinking during the EEG.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  Careful review of the patient may be helpful to determine if the symptoms that she experienced were typical of her eye blinking.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 46-year-old male with multiple medical problems, chronic pain syndrome, radiculopathy, hyperlipidemia on multiple medications.  The patient has many different episodes that seem to be seizures, including confusional spells, tremulousness.  Also reported seizures with unilateral shaking, but ability to converse.

Heart rate 66 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Photic stimulation was performed which produced no abnormal discharges.
Please note that the during the entire recording the patient did have some intermittent muscle artifact that could only be seen over the entire right hemisphere and not on the left side of the brain.  There is no video correlate to this asymmetric muscle artifact.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the EEG did show some asymmetric muscle artifact which may represent weakness of the left facial muscles.  Please correlate clinically these findings.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 26-year-old male diagnosed 2 years ago at Mercer Hospital with epilepsy. IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old right-handed man with a history of head trauma from car accident.  The patient stated that he started having seizure-like activity after car accident.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage II of sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 12 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes, sleep spindles, and posts.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through a stage 2 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy, if seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Portable EEG.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old male with a history of seizures and hypertension presents with seizure-like activities described as acting weird, staring, confusion, and EMS noted generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include phenobarbital and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through a stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency and 30-35 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is presence of low amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of the vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles. Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic metabolic hypoxic or infectious encephalopathy, alternatively it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including phenobarbital or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform discharges abnormalities or seizures were captured during this record.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.  The absence of epileptiform activities or seizures does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with a past medical history of adult onset seizures who presented with 2 episodes of generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  The patient remained lethargic.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG monitoring was performed using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Records were daily reviewed for EEG abnormalities and clinical events, wakefulness, stage 2 sleep, and a slow wave sleep were captured.  There was an automated spike and seizure detection system in place as well as the patient activated alarm system.  The patient was drowsy with short periods of wakefulness during this recording.
Interictal EEG:  In the most alert state, there was a posterior dominant rhythm with a frequency of 9-9.5 Hz and 25-40 microvolts seen in the occipital region, which attenuated with eye opening.  There was presence of low-amplitude diffuse beta frequency, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness, stage 1 and a stage 2 sleep were seen during the most part of this recording.  Stage 1 sleep was characterized by the disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background and absence of eye blink and muscle artifact, vertex sharp waves, and POSTS.  Stage 2 sleep was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles, and POSTS.  The deeper stages of sleep have characterized by increasing amounts of delta frequency activity.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures were captured during this recording.  Heart rate was 90 to 110 beats per minute.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  No clinical events were captured during this recording.  The patient was drowsy, but arousable by calling the patient.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG monitoring study capturing short periods of wakefulness and for the most part of the recording drowsiness stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  There were no epileptiform activities or seizures noted during this recording.  This EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are of a clinical concern, a repeat prolonged video EEG monitoring may be helpful.  Please note that the patient was tachycardiac.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted with an episode of transient dizziness.  Past history of hypertension, asthma and a psychiatric illness.

In addition, very brief stage I sleep was seen, with vertex waves and then a transition in and out of stage I sleep. IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging but normal EEG.

The transitions in and out of stage II sleep may reflect sleep deprivation or an underlying sleep disturbance, which could be correlated with this patient's clinical picture.  To obtain a better quality EEG, a repeat study, when the patient has had her hair weaves removed, is suggested.

CONDITION OF RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed. Stepped photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant consists of a well-formed and modulated 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient, with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), vertex waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  A single EKG lead demonstrates a heart rate fewer than 60 beats a minute.
FINDINGS:  No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep electroencephalogram.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine electroencephalogram does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Heart rate with fewer than 60 beats per minute is captured on a single-electrocardiogram lead.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old male with a history of head trauma, adult-onset epilepsy, and likely nonepileptic seizures as well.  The patient typically has seizures after encounters with the health care system and has many adverse reactions to antiepileptic drugs.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, oxycodone, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was a very drowsy patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there was a 10.5-Hz alpha rhythm.  The patient quickly transitioned to a drowsy pattern with prominent slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves were noted in stage 1 sleep.  As the patient drifted off to sleep, there was an involuntary jerk of the right leg. This was not associated with epileptiform features.  Cognitive testing was performed at the end to make sure that the patient was maximally awake and there was an awake pattern and then the patient quickly started to become a little drowsy with slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.  Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform activity was noted.  Sleep myoclonus was noted on one occasion which does not carry an EEG correlate.  This patient appears to be excessively drowsy which could be related to sleep deprivation or the use of opiate medications as described above.

Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  A stage II was characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.
