CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013.  Apparently she fainted and was on the floor for 15 seconds and then was observed to shake.  Of note, during the recording here in the laboratory, there was a brief episode of right hemibody tingling.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The recording start time was 11:29 a.m.  The recording end time was 12 noon.  The recording length was 25 minutes.
As the record opens there is a well formed and symmetric 9-10 Hz  posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness.  She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela.  During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges.  The patient's heart rate ranged from 70-90 beats during the record epic.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does no rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  The brief clinical event of right hemibody numbness and tingling were not associated with changes in the background cerebral activity.  Thus, this event is likely a nonepileptic event.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old man with history of seizures has been seizure-free for more than a year with mild mental retardation and developmental delay.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage 1 sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hz seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 1 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG, does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman with a first ever tonic,clonic seizure at home on an unknown date, awoke in an ambulance.  Restless leg syndrome, chronic back pain.

Using frequency analysis, the alpha rhythm is notched and includes an 8.5 Hz and a 9-9.5 Hz peak.  This is not something that is otherwise easy to identify visually.
Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in background slowing and a few bursts of paroxysmal theta.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing bilaterally.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral  driving.
Heart rate 102 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The bifed alpha population is something picked up using computer tool and is not something that is otherwise seen visually.  No seizures or epileptiform features were seen.  To further characterize this patient's epileptiform activity, a repeat tracing with more extensive sleep may be of value.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage 10 Hz alpha rhythm in the background with generous low voltage beta. In fact, the patient seemed to be falling asleep at the end of hyperventilation with beta spindles characteristic of stage II sleep.  Other features of sleep included vertex waves and more subtle POSTS.  Sustained stage II sleep was more abundant in those vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS were noted.
The patient remained drowsy throughout photic stimulation which nonetheless, elicited a driving response.  By the end of photic stimulation, she was drifting back into stage II sleep.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This patient appears to be extremely sleepy.  Clinical correlation for hypersomnolence may be appropriate, but a sleep-deprived EEG could also produce these findings.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since the age of 8.  Most recent seizure June/July 2012 with fainting, falling, and shaking.  Now 4 months pregnant.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
TECHNICAL:  Impedances for most of the electrodes were satisfactory, but this EEG was problematic with a great degree of muscle artifact when the patient was awake.  As the patient went off to sleep, there was still muscle artifact picked up in the left scalp electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems described above, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of focal frontal central beta.  Wicket was noted as the patient became drowsy.  Other features with drowsiness include rhythmic central theta.  The electrode artifact did not drop out in stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Brief stage II sleep included vertex waves with spindles.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was remarkable for a great deal of muscle artifact.  Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The wicket is a normal finding.  Given the degree of muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study capturing perhaps more prolonged
sleep or with other mechanisms to alleviate the muscle artifact is suggested.  Alternatively, comparison with this individual's childhood EEGs may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman, seizure free for 1-2 years.  Characteristics of seizures included oral automatisms and tongue biting, positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, multivitamins, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a routine outpatient EEG with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1 and T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, rhythmic midtemporal theta activity was noted with 5 Hz activity seen infrequently, left more so than the right.  Stage 2 sleep was captured at the close of the recording with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  No temporal theta was noted at that time.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but produced vigorous bilateral driving response with supraharmonic driving.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this subject which did not identify epileptiform activity.  The rhythmic midtemporal theta noted in drowsiness is a normal variant.
